## Redrawing of Borders and Creation of New States

The political aftermath of WWI saw a comprehensive redrawing of European borders, guided by treaties such as the Treaty of Versailles (1919), the Treaty of Saint-Germain (Austria), and the Treaty of Trianon (Hungary). These treaties aimed to recognize national self-determination but were also influenced by political considerations of the victorious Allied powers.

### Key New Countries and Territorial Changes

| New Country/Entity           | Origin/Source Empire                      | Notes                                                                                   |
|-----------------------------|------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| **Poland**                  | Formerly partitioned by Russia, Germany, and Austria-Hungary | Re-established as an independent nation for the first time in over a century ([AlphaHistory, n.d.](https://alphahistory.com/worldwar1/post-war-europe/)) |
| **Czechoslovakia**          | Austro-Hungarian Empire                   | Formed from Czech and Slovak lands ([RealClearHistory, 2018](https://www.realclearhistory.com/articles/2018/11/29/how_world_war_i_changed_map_of_the_world_389.html#!)) |
| **Yugoslavia** (Kingdom of Serbs, Croats, and Slovenes) | Austro-Hungarian Empire and Serbia      | Combined several South Slavic peoples; later fragmented in the late 20th century ([eNotes, n.d.](https://www.enotes.com/homework-help/explain-two-ways-map-europe-changed-after-world-646922)) |
| **Baltic States** (Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania) | Russian Empire                          | Declared independence following Russian collapse ([VOA News, 2014](https://www.voanews.com/a/how-wwi-changed-the-map-of-europe/1970075.html)) |
| **Finland**                 | Russian Empire                           | Declared independence in 1917 ([Colors-NewYork.com, 2021](https://colors-newyork.com/how-did-europe-borders-change-after-ww1/)) |
| **Austria and Hungary**     | Austro-Hungarian Empire                   | Became separate republics ([RealClearHistory, 2018](https://www.realclearhistory.com/articles/2018/11/29/how_world_war_i_changed_map_of_the_world_389.html#!)) |
| **Turkey**                  | Ottoman Empire                           | Successor state of Ottoman Empire ([Colors-NewYork.com, 2021](https://colors-newyork.com/how-did-europe-borders-change-after-ww1/)) |

### Territorial Redistributions Affecting Germany

Germany suffered significant territorial losses as a result of the Treaty of Versailles:

| Territory Lost             | Recipient/Status                          | Notes                                                                                   |
|---------------------------|------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| Alsace-Lorraine           | France                                   | Returned after German annexation in 1871 ([EffectosOfWWI, n.d.](https://effectosofwwi.weebly.com/ww1-political.html)) |
| Eupen and Malmedy         | Belgium                                  | Transferred to Belgium ([EffectosOfWWI, n.d.](https://effectosofwwi.weebly.com/ww1-political.html)) |
| Northern Schleswig        | Denmark                                  | Transferred following plebiscite ([EffectosOfWWI, n.d.](https://effectosofwwi.weebly.com/ww1-political.html)) |
| West Prussia, Posen, Upper Silesia | Poland                          | Territories given to newly re-established Poland ([eNotes, n.d.](https://www.enotes.com/homework-help/what-did-treaty-versailles-say-what-were-effects-442949)) |
| Saar Basin                | League of Nations administration          | Coal-rich region administered internationally for 15 years ([TreatyOfVersailles.weebly.com, n.d.](https://treatyofversice.weebly.com/political-effects.html)) |
| Danzig                    | Free City under League of Nations         | Semi-autonomous city-state ([EffectosOfWWI, n.d.](https://effectosofwwi.weebly.com/ww1-political.html)) |
| Memel                     | Lithuania                                | Transferred to Lithuania ([EffectosOfWWI, n.d.](https://effectosofwwi.weebly.com/ww1-political.html)) |
| Overseas Colonies         | Lost to Allied powers                      | Germany lost all overseas colonies ([TreatyOfVersailles.weebly.com, n.d.](https://treatyofversice.weebly.com/political-effects.html)) |

In total, Germany lost approximately 13% of its European territory and was reduced to about 10% of its pre-war population ([EffectosOfWWI, n.d.](https://effectosofwwi.weebly.com/ww1-political.html); [TreatyOfVersailles.weebly.com, n.d.](https://treatyofversice.weebly.com/political-effects.html)).

