## Conclusion

World War I fundamentally transformed the political and geographical landscape of Europe. The war ended the dominance of four major empires and led to the creation of numerous new nation-states, redrawing the map of Europe in ways that still resonate today. The treaties that followed the war, especially the Treaty of Versailles, imposed significant territorial and political changes, particularly on Germany, sowing the seeds for future instability.

While the post-war order aimed to promote national self-determination and peace, it often resulted in new ethnic tensions and political fragmentation. The League of Nations, although a pioneering attempt at international governance, lacked the power to enforce lasting peace.

In my assessment, the changes brought by WWI were both necessary and transformative but were implemented with political compromises that failed to address underlying ethnic and nationalist conflicts fully. This fragile peace set the stage for the geopolitical upheavals of the mid-20th century, including World War II.

